    <h2 id="intro">Introduction</h2>
    <mark>These three paragraphs to be edited / reworked - PC. </mark>  
    <p>The project that was to be known as “FreeBMD” began as a test and development system on RootsWeb in late-1998; and in the three or four months before it went live, a <strong>FreeBMD-News page</strong> was started on RootsWeb to keep potential volunteers informed on its progess. Shortly after the FreeBMD system went live, these RootsWeb pages were copied onto a page on FreeBMD, also called <strong>FreeBMD News</strong>. The RootsWeb version of the page also continued, but neither versions were updated after 2015. However, in October 2014 the FreeUKGenealogy website started up; and that began to carry FreeBMD-related news.</p>
   <p> We have a separate page on FreeBMD2 devoted to newsworthy events which took place from 2015, onwards: the <strong>News page</strong>. The starting date for that page was chosen firstly because this was the year our current Executive Director, Pat Reynolds, was appointed Executive Director of Free UK Genealogy — the parent of FreeBMD.</p>
    <p>In addition, there was a need to move the older material to archive. So, this page, together with the <strong>Release Notes Page</strong>, also provides a depository, or archive, for older material that has ‘dropped’ off the <strong>FreeBMD2 News Page</strong>.</p>

    <h2 id="briefHistory">A brief history of FreeBMD</h2>
    <h3 id="howItstarted">How did FreeBMD start</h3>
    <p>In 1997, the International Internet Genealogical Society (IIGS) was founded by Dr. Brian Leverich. In additions, back in 1993, Brian Leverich and Karen Isaacson had founded, and were the owners, of RootsWeb. Brian was interested in making use of the recent innovation the World Wide Web — the software behind that had entered the public domain in 1993. So, in 1997 Brian and the society’s members were giving consideration to the possibilities of using ‘crowd-sourcing’ for genealogy  — making use of people from around the world to supply transcriptions; and building genealogical data bases that would allow anyone, anywhere, to search that data. </p>
   <p>In 1998, FreeBMD was the brainchild of Ben Laurie, Camilla Gemmingen von Massenbach and Graham Hart. Its main aim was to provide free access for everyone to the information held in the Indexes to the General Registry Office (G.R.O.) registrations of birth, marriage and death. These Indexes, at the time, were held as large printed volumes in St. Catherine's House, London; and in the form of microfiche sets of births, marriages or deaths by quarter-year, sold by the G.R.O. and its successors under licence — the licence prohibited the purchaser from making or providing any copies to other people.</p>
    <p>Also in 1998, Michael Whitfield Foster (R.I.P.) — who was born in the United Kingdom, but had later moved to New Zealand — published his book: <em>“A Comedy of Errors” or The Marriage Records of England and Wales 1837 — 1899</em>. It presented his research, the findings and the recommendations from his (first) G.R.O. research project — authorised by the Office for National Statistics — which he undertook at the G.R.O. Southport some six years earlier.</p> 
     <p>It had long been suspected that there were many errors and omissions in the G.R.O. Index. His research showed that there were. He devoted a chapter with his recommendations as to how these might be corrected or mitigated; and offered a proposal for further research.</p>
    <p>Of importance to the FreeBMD project, Michael, both through personal research and the help of local volunteers in England — recruited through the World Wide Web — had amassed a computer database of <mark> add numbers - PC</mark> marriage records. Copies some of marriage records had come from the local parish registers or from LDS copies of these registers and some were purchased from the relevant local Register Office. In addition, he used the LDS / <em>FamilySearch</em> microfilm copies of the G.R.O. Index to find matching, or mismatching, G.R.O. Index entries for each of these marriages.</p>
    <p>The first hurdle for Ben, Camilla and Graham was to gain the necessary permissions from the Office for National Statistics (O.N.S.) to make use of the G.R.O. births, marriages and deaths Indexes. An initial response was received from the O.N.S. on 18th May 1998; and the final agreement received on 13 July 1998.</p>
   <p class="push-half--bottom">This agreement limited the project to:</p>
        <ul>
           <li> only publishing G.R.O. Index records that were over one hundred years old</li>
           <li> providing access to the records free of charge</li>
           <li> acknowledging on the website, the Crown Copyright on these records</li>
           <li>requiring users of the website not to copy or transfer images without prior permission from the O.N.S.</li>
       </ul>
   <p>Then work could start on developing the structures and the systems to allow this to happen.</p>
    
   <h3>Revenue streams</h3>
    <p> <mark> Not sure if a sub-section is needed, or it's just distributed throughout article - PC. </mark> </p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">This started off as a volunteer driven project with no staff and no premisses:</p>
      <ul>
           <li> at the start, RootsWeb web-hosted the site, provided a computer, the web bandwidth and ... </li>
           <li> at the start, FreeBMD could not show images of the G.R.O. Indexes and transcribers sourced their own</li>
