    <h2 id="development">1998: Developing the structures and the system</h2>
    <h3>Dividing up the work </h3>
     <p> In mid-July 1998, when the final agreement was received from O.N.S., work could start in earnest. Camilla was responsible for the ‘organisational side’ and Ben and Graham  for the ‘programming’ side of the project. ‘Programming’ included designing the formats of data, data storage, searching and presentation of results.</p>
   <p>There was also a need to consider the ‘project structure’. The transcription side was to be set up with volunteer transcriber in syndicates, each under the control of a <strong>Syndicate coordinator</strong>, who would control and track the progress of allocations. Above those was a <strong>Syndicate Coordinator,</strong> who would track year-allocations and deal with syndicate coordinator questions. In addition, there was a need for Quality assurance systems&#160; .....</p>
        
  <h3 id="RootsWeb">RootsWeb web-hosts the FreeBMD test system </h3>
     <p> Since 1993, the <a href="https://home.rootsweb.com" target="_blank">free online community: RootsWeb (opens in a New Page)</a> provided hosted websites, messaging boards and mailing lists.</p>
     <p>RootWeb, from the start of the FreeBMD project, provided and web hosted — without charge — a dedicated server used to develop the FreeBMD test system. This was a computer with an Intel 486-based processor running at 66 Mhz. </p>
    <p>RootsWeb would continue to host the live version of FreeBMD; and provide FreeBMD with mailing list facilities and messaging boards facilities.</p>
    <p class="islet islet--bordered">You can <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancestry.com#RootsWeb" target="_blank"> find out more about RootsWeb (and Ancestry) on wikipedia's Ancestry page (opens in a new page).</a> </p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">On <strong>30 September 1998</strong> <a href="https://www.freebmd.org.uk/980926.html" target="_blank">a RootsWeb review stated (archive page from our old FreeBMD site, opens in a New Tab):</a> </p>
     <ul>
        <li>“The FreeBMD project is expected to take forever probably, and the next 15 years certainly”</li>
        <li>“At this stage, FreeBMD is developing the database, records management and search engine software as well as designing the Web site. FreeBMD uses Mike Foster's transcriptions as test data”</li>
      </ul> 
   <p> On <strong> 16 October 1998,</strong> an announcement mailing list was sent out on RootsWeb for those interested in the FreeBMD project without being involved in its management. This will be for volunteers and those with a general interest in our happenings.</p> 
   <p class="push-half--bottom"> By the end of <strong> 17 October 1998</strong>: </p>
      <ul>
        <li> submitter details were added to the search engine</li>
        <li>work was in progress for managing submitter information, but in the meantime anyone with test data can submit it now — just write to Ben for a login </li>
        <li> a new input format of One Name Studies was been added — this allows us to take advantage of the ‘semi-sequenced’ nature of one-name data</li>
         <li>RootsWeb are to supply a new, faster machine for the FreeBMD Test system.</li>
      </ul>
     <p>Over the three days, <strong>21, 22 and 23 October 1998,</strong> a database status page was added; the system was amended to allow underscores in file names; a statistics page was added; and the system was amended to allow "uncertain characters" in names.</p>
     <p> On <strong>25 October 1998,</strong> a moderated mailing list (<strong>FreeBMD-News</strong>) was set up on RootsWeb to allow interested people to keep up to date with the progress of the FreeBMD project. </p>
    <p class="islet islet--bordered"> FreeBMD set up more mailing lists on RootsWeb. You can view an — unindexed other than be date — archived versions of these mailing lists on the Ancestry RootsWeb archive <mark> PC to rework and add hyperlinks.</mark> </p>
   <p>On <strong>3 December 1998,</strong>  added tentative transcriber allocation pages; and the test system passes 80,000 records!</p>
   <p> On <strong> 5 December 1998,</strong> added some checking for validity of volume numbers. However, this may invalidate some existing data.</p>
  <p> On <strong>19 December 1998,</strong> RootsWeb provided a new computer for FreeBMD! This was planned anyway, but needed to accelerated by the unfortunate demise of the test computer. Thanks, RootsWeb!  Unfortunately, in the crash, the test data that had been submitted was lost. However, none of the web pages, or programs disappeared for good.</p>

  <h3 id="FreeBMD now live"> FreeBMD goes live</h3>
   <p> On <strong>30 December 1998,</strong> we revamped the website to reflect our live status and to credit RootsWeb more fully. Our new URL became http://FreeBMD.RootsWeb.com </p>
    <p class="islet islet--teal"> Note: FreeBMD no longer uses this web address and it can not be accessed.</p>
    
    <p>At the start of the project, transcribers had to source their own copies of the Indexes. Sourcing copies of the G.R.O. Indexes was helped in March 1999, the Office for National Statistics issued FreeBMD with a letter which would allow existing holders of G.R.O. microfiche Indexes to supply copies from their holdings to  ......</p>
   
   <h2 id="firstYearLive">1999: The first year of live running</h2>
   <p>David Mayall joined <mark> this year(?) but when? - PC </mark> and became an ‘owner of the system’ that was running on its webhost: RootsWeb. The <a href="https://www.freebmd.org.uk/ctroles.html" target="_blank">Project Team page, on the old FreeBMD site (FreeBMD page opens in a new Tab)</a> list Ben Laurie, Camilla von Massenbach, Graham Hart and David Mayall as Co-Founder and Trustees of FreeUKGenealogy. FreeUKGenealogy was the new name adopted in 2014 by FreeBMD, the charity formed in 2003 from FreeBMD.</p>
   <h3>We get our own logo</h3>
   <p> On <strong>15 January 1999,</strong> FreeBMD finally gets a logo. It was available in three sizes — small, medium and large — and was to be used by calling up its URL, rather than copying it. </p>
