   <h3 id="GRO-permissions">O.N.S. issues a letter allowing FreeBMD to obtain copies from G.R.O. Microfiche or Microfilm</h3>
   <p>On 26th March 1999, we received a letter from the Office for National Statistics providing a formal process for holders of the G.R.O. Index to supply copies to FreeBMD for transcribing. This would allow us, for example, to go to a library that had bought a copy of the G.R.O. Index under licence; and they would gain permission to issue specified copies to FreeBMD or its transcribers. <mark>To be expanded, see https://www.freebmd.org.uk/Permission.html - PC. </mark> </p>
   
  <h3> January to April 1999 enhancements</h3>
   <p>On <strong>3 January 1999</strong>, the marriages search form was enhanced to include spouse matching; 1898 was made the last valid year; and progress graphs were added to the system.</p>
     <p>On <strong>16th and 17th January 1999</strong>, respectively, ‘District synonyms’ were added to the system — that is, a way of mapping known variants of District names onto a single "standard" spelling; and a District name checking routine was ‘enabled’ on the database.</p>
  <p>On <strong>26 January 1999</strong>, an Age range at Death option was added to the deaths search form.</p>
  <p>On <strong>27 February 1999</strong>, the following enhancements were added to the search form: quarters were added to the start and end dates; only list the page in the same year and quarter on the page link; and "All Types" and "All Districts" were added to the list boxes on the search page.</p>
   <p>On <strong>28 February 1999</strong>, the wild card character <strong>*</strong> could be used in a district name; and we hit 90,000 entries!</p>
  <p> On <strong>11th March 1999</strong> 100,000 entries was reached.</p>
    <p> <strong>18th April 1999</strong>, Graham has recently taken over the syndicate and allocation management and Andrew has recently set up a mailing list ready for the Syndicates. Today, we have added scans of the ONS and LDS order forms for buying microfiche and microfilm.  We've started a regular Internet Relay Chat (IRC) channel, on the IRC server hosted by the IIGS and sponsored by RootsWeb. This IRC channel was to be found at: #FreeBMD,&#160; on test.links.org, port 6667.</p> 
     <p class="islet islet--teal"> Note: FreeBMD no longer uses this IRC Channel, and it is can not be accessed.</p>

